  "introduction": "Imagine you are a chemist tasked with creating a specific medicine. If your measurement is off by even a tiny bit, it could be ineffective or dangerous. Today, we start our journey into Chemistry not just as 'mixing stuff', but as the science of precise matter and measurement. Let's see how we can tell if something is pure or mixed, and why writing down numbers correctly matters more than you think!",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "This session covers the fundamental classification of matter into elements, compounds, and mixtures (homogeneous/heterogeneous). It also introduces the concept of significant figures to ensure measurements reflect true precision.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Matter is classified as Pure Substances or Mixtures based on composition.",
      "Pure substances are Elements or Compounds; Mixtures can be Homogeneous or Heterogeneous.",
      "Significant figures represent the certainty of a measurement, including one estimated digit."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "Matter is anything that has mass and occupies space. We categorize it to understand its behavior. Pure substances have fixed chemical compositions (e.g., Water is always H2O). Mixtures are physical combinations where components retain their identity (e.g., Salt water can be separated by evaporation). Homogeneous mixtures look the same throughout, while heterogeneous ones do not. In terms of measurement, no instrument gives an exact number; there is always uncertainty. Significant figures capture this precision: all certain digits plus one uncertain digit are significant. For example, 12.5 cm has three sig figs."
  },
